claves. Orsi explores the ambitions and dilemmas of these women as they dealt with the pressures of the Depression and the Second World War, made modern marriages for themselves, entered the workplace, took care of relatives in their old neighborhoods, and raised children in circumstances very different from those of their mothers and grandmothers. Drawing on testimonies written in the periodicals devoted to St. Jude and on interviews with women who felt their lives were changed by St. Jude's intervention, Orsi shows how devotion to St. Jude enabled these women to negotiate their way amid the conflicting expectations of their two cultures-American and Catholic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300162691423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300162691.jpg  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles